\pard\plain \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\sl259\slmult1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid10058256 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 Reminiscences
\par 
\par of <hi rend="underline">George Nidever</hi> and <hi rend="underline">Charles Brown</hi> of the Early History of Santa Barbara and the Fining [Finding] of the Woman (Indian) on San Nicholas Island.
\par 
\par Q. What is your name?
\par 
\par A. My name is George Nidever. I was born in the St<del rend="strikethrough">/</del>ate of Tennessee in 1802.
\par 
\par Q. How old were you when you left home?
\par 
\par A. I was a boy, quite small, not more than 10 years old, when I left Tennessee and went to Arkansas and Mexico.
\par 
\par Q. What did you do when you were in Arkansas and Mexico?
\par 
\par A. <del rend="striket
hrough">Folled</del>Followed hunting. Traveled about from the time I was 18 years old and have been traveling ever since. I went to Texas and came back to Arkansas. There was a company coming to the Rocky Mts. in 1830. We traveled in Arkansas, given by tr
eaty to the Cherokee Indians. I had to leave.
\par 
\par Q. What was your father's occupation?
\par 
\par A. Farmer
\par 
\par Q. That means hunter in those days?
\par 
\par A. Yes - small farmer - not like they do now.
\par 
\par Q. What started you to come to California?
\par 
\par A. It was a company coming to the Rocky Mountains for two years to trap beaver. I was a good shot and they wanted me to come out.
\par 
\par Q. What did you come out here to do?
\par 
\par A. The company were nearly all killed. Capt. Walker was coming across and they did not make much and said they were coming to California. Well I came with them.
\par 
\par Q. How many where there in the company?
\par 
\par A. Thirty-six when they came here.
\par 
\par Q. How many started? Ans. 48.
\par 
\par <del rend="strikethrough">A</del>Q. What become of the rest? Ans. Some stopped.
\par 
\par Q.Did you meet any Indians on the way? Ans. Yes.
\par 
\par Q. Did you have any trouble with them?
\par 
\par A. We were troubled all the while with them till we came to California. There was some trouble here but not with the Indians, but Indians from the north.
\par 
\par Q. Did you have any fights with them? Ans. Yes.
\par 
\par Q. Did you shoot at them? Ans. Yes, we killed 34 in one place.
\par 
\par Q. What tribe? Ans. Piutes.
\par 
\par Q. Did they kill any of your folks? Ans. No, they did not.
\par 
\par Q. You had guns and they had bows and arrows? Ans. Yes, and spades.
\par 
\par Q. What year was that when you came here?
\par 
\par A. 1834. Came into Monterey first. Struck the coast there at St. Joseph. Monterey was the capital. Struck the coast at a place called Gilroy.
\par 
\par Q. Packed, did you? Ans. Yes.
\par 
\par Q. Did you walk a good deal of the way? Ans. Yes, we had to kill our meat all the way.
\par 
\par Q. Did you live on meat all the way? Ans. Nothing but meat. Did not take any flour. 
\par 
\par Q. Was there any time when you could not find any game?
\par 
\par A. There was a time when we could not find much, but always killed something. 
\par 
\par Q. What did you kill - what kind of meat? Ans. Buffalo, elk, deer, bear.
\par 
\par Q. How long were you coming from Tennessee here?
\par 
\par A. I left about 10 years old. It [I] got here in '34  - several years on the way. Sometimes we would be stopped 2 or 3 years in a place trapping; catched (cached?) a good many beaver but lost them by the Indians.
\par 
\par Q. What did they do? Ans. Took the skins. They were worth $4.00 a lb.
\par 
\par Q. When you got here did you find any Americans?
\par 
\par A. Some Americans in 1834, about 50 or 60 in the country.
\par 
\par Q. How many Indians did you find here? Ans. More than white men.
\par 
\par Q. Ask him if he remembers anything about the old Missions. Tell us anything you remember about it.
\par 
\par A. They had cattle and horses. The priests had charge of everything; raised corn and wheat; raised enough to live on; had a good many cattle and lived on them.
\par 
\par Q. What did you do when you came here?
\par 
\par A. Hunted sea otter 20 or 30 years. It must be learned; we had no rifles like we have now, but one-barrel old fashioned rifle.
\par 
\par Q. How mahy Indians did you ever kill?
\par 
\par A. I could not tell how many. I know I killed four. There were only 36 of us; we had got
 well used to the Indians. We wanted to get them on us. Finally they followed us and finally they intended to take us. We did not know any names and that was called Mary Run, Salt Lake, and there was a trail and the trail went through a bunch of willows. 
W
e knew they intended to take us and at about 200 yards we turned off, and as soon as we turned off they came out. They l<del rend="strikethrough">k</del>ived in villages. Every village <del rend="strikethrough">g</del>has its captain. They came up. The fi
r
st party coing up we met them, 15 of us, and about 200 yards away we tied the horses altog<del rend="strikethrough">o</del>ether.  There were 15 of us and these 15 were choice shots. They came walking right up within 40 or 50 yards of us and they were kin
d
 of falling to - every fellow had his hands full of arrows - and we commenced firing all 15 shots at once. There were 34 Indians killed, the rest ran away. You were asking me how many I killed. About two days a fterward [afterward] we were out, me and the
 
captain. There were five. I got off to one side to the left and walked up to a place where we were to meet. They had not come yet. I saw two Indians coming. I thought they were after me, but they had not seen me. They ran along and kept looking back. I th
ought they had shot a man and so I thought I would kill one. I had a brother killed by them. Finally they came to a point of the hill. I shot. I killed them both. They just fell and rolled.
\par 
\par Q. Where about did you hit them?
\par 
\par A. The first was shot on the left side and killed instantly.
\par 
\par Q. {\*\atrfstart 397166852}Ask him if he did not see any friendly Indians, any he had confidence in.
\par 
\par A. No, could not trust any. There was what is called the Snake Indians, about the best, but could not trust them.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 {\*\atrfend 397166852}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn 
{\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166852}{\*\atndate 656911755}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9140007 Indians as savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par 
\par Q. Ask him if he had anything to do with the Apache Indians.
\par 
\par A. Yes, coming through New Mexico. Saw some there.
\par 
\par Q. Were not they friendly? A. Not very. They would steal.
\par 
\par Q. <del rend="strikethrough">Was it there you stll</del>Was it there you settled down first?
\par 
\par A. Yes. I came to Monterey and went up to San Francisco; was at San Joaquin in a boat and come down to San Francisco. The ship California was there and was coming down to Santa Barbara and saw some Americans and told them they ought t
o come here. When I came here it was in 1835 in the city of Santa Barbara. There were 17 or 18 at first the year I came to Santa Barbara, 85.
\par 
\par Q. This womn - how came she to be left on the Island?
\par 
\par A. Sparks took them all down to the beach, She had a child back on the land and wanted to go back and finally they let her go and she did not come back and they went away and she was left there. Sparkes came and said there was a woman left on the island. 
All expected she could not live.
\par 
\par Q. Who was Sparkes and how came to to go for the Indians?
\par 
\par A. The Mexicans sent them to bring them off. The schooner got lost just afterwards. They calculated to go back. All thought that the woman would not live long, so they did not go back. The schooner went to San Francisco and got lost.
\par 
\par Q. Why did you want to bring the Indians off anyway?
\par 
\par A. They wanted them at the Mission anyhow and the Government sent to fetch them off.
\par 
\par Q. Did the Indians go to work in the Mission, these particular ones?
\par 
\par A. They sent them to work different places, those they brought off.
\par 
\par Q. How did the Indians get on there in the first place?
\par 
\par A. Born and raised there - never been on the coast.
\par 
\par Q. Did you see the Indians on there before they were taken off?
\par 
\par A. No, I never saw them.
\par 
\par Q. How came you to find this woman was left there? Did you see her tracks?
\par 
\par A. Yes, it was three times before I found her. I went over. The priests here wanted me to hunt for her.
\par 
\par A. What priest was it? A. Father Gonzales, after Sanchez.
\par 
\par Q. How long was it before you found her after you want to the Island?
\par 
\par A. I found her pretty quick. We had been all over the Island and it was 12 o' clock I suppose. It was very pretty weather. Capt. Brown was with me. Me and h<del rend="strikethrough">o</del>im walked over to the head of the Island and we saw a track where 
s
he had been to the water. We did not find her that evening. Fenally [Finally] went and brought over several Indians on board of the crew - t<del rend="strikethrough">s</del>wo or three white men the rest Indians. We took all of them ashore except the cook
.
 We thought she would try and hide and we s<del rend="strikethrough">a</del>cattered off two or three hundred yards apart. She had a little house made of brush and had a fire; sitting by the fire with a little knife; she was working with it; she had a bon
e
. All came up and looked at her well. She had a heap of roots. That is what she lived on and had little sacks to carry them in. As soon as we sat down she put a lump of them to roast on the fire. Finally we got ready to go and we made signs f<del rend="st
r
ikethrough">/</del>or her to come with us. She picked up her things to take them on board. She did not appear to be seasick at all and was conte<del rend="strikethrough">ted</del>nted. Next day we moved ashore and stayed there a month and killed a good ma
ny otter. She appeared to like everything we had to eat. When we got ready to come we made signs we were coming and she was very willing to come. She came here.
\par 
\par Q. W hat [What] did she say when she came to the beach and saw them on horseback?
\par 
\par A. She said it in her own tongue; looked up and down the coast and thought it was an island. It was a month or five weeks after she landed before she died.
\par 
\par Q. What did she have on when you found her on the Island?
\par 
\par A. Had her dress made of bird skins, out of what they <del rend="strikethrough">XXXX</del> call shag (a species of black duck). We made her clothes right off; made her petticoats right off. Gave her shirts.
\par 
\par Q. What did she make the petticoats of? A. Clothes we had.
\par 
\par Q. Men's clothes would not make good petticoats. A: No, cut them up, y<hi rend="underline">ou</hi>/see.
\par 
\par Q. Dressed her instyle [in style], did you? A. Yes, made her presentable here.
\par 
\par Q. How did she sew those bird skins together?
\par 
\par A. Got<del rend="strikethrough">n</del>the [Got the] sinews of a seal. It made quite a nice thread and she had needles of bone.
\par 
\par Q. What did she do with the dress?
\par 
\par A. The dress the priests have. I think they sent it to Rome. My wife <del rend="strikethrough">lest</del> let them have them all, her needles and all the t
hings. she [She] had a demijohn to carry her water, held a gallon or 1 1/2 gallons, made out of rushes and stopped with asphaltum. She was maing [making] another. Wal<del rend="strikethrough">l</del>ked up and down. She would walk every day. Finally I see
 she had a fire made and had small round stones heating of them, and she put them in the asphaltum and threw in these hot stones and it would run all over and make them as tight as a demijohn.
\par 
\par Q. How did she make fire? A. Out of sticks.
\par 
\par Q. No <del rend="strikethrough">maches</del>matches? A. No, she made it with a stick rubbing a stick. I have done it myself.
\par 
\par Q. Did you bring those things off that she used for water?
\par 
\par A. Yes, was fetched here. Scattered in different places, different persons getting them. {\*\atrfstart 397166853}She said her child was eaten up by wolves or wild dogs, which were on the Island.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 {\*\atrfend 397166853}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166853}{\*\atndate 656911762}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9140007 Sings easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par 
\par Q. Ask him if none of the Indians here understood what she said.
\par 
\par A. No, there was none of the Indians here that understood her good; I tried to find some tribe that could talk to her and finally got some wo<del rend="strikethrough">k</del>man that could talk a little.
\par 
\par Q. Where did that old woman come from that could talk to her a little?
\par 
\par A. She was raised on San Nicholas.
\par 
\par Q. You say there was one woman who could understand her a little?
\par 
\par A. She was fetched from some of the islands.
\par 
\par Q. {\*\atrfstart 397166854}Did she tell that woman her child was eatent up by the dogs? A. No.
\par 
\par Q. How did you know?
\par 
\par A. From her signs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 {\*\atrfend 397166854}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166854}{\*\atndate 656911763}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid9140007 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9140007 Signs easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
 She thought that the dosg [dogs] had eaten it. There are a great many dogs there, wild dogs; they were poisoned off some years after.
\par 
\par Q. She used to live with you till she died?
\par 
\par A. Yes, died right here in this room.
\par 
\par Q. What seemed to be the matter with her?
\par 
\par A. Just kind of give up. Could not tell what was the matter. Indians when they are sick naturally give up, don't care if they live or not.
\par 
\par Q. How old was she? A. About 50; that's what the priests thought.
\par 
\par Q. Did you hunt any after that?
\par 
\par A. Yes, killed lots of otter there, 7<delrend="strikethrough">p</del>0 in one month.
\par 
\par Q. Have you got any Indian relics here? A. None now except this (shows).
\par 
\par Q. Where did you get it. A. It came from the islands, I don't know which island.
\par 
\par Q. Who found it?
\par 
\par A. I don't know. It is a weapon to fix in a stick. I was in the war with the Mexicans. This is a medal (shows medal). Soldiers in the Mexican war had them. I was in California here with Fremont. The Mexican war commenced in 1846. I entered in 1848.
\par 
\par Q. Where did you come from? A. A native of Pennsylvania.
\par 
\par A. What descent was he? A. German.
\par 
\par Q. Could you tell me something about otter hunting? I expect you have seen some pretty hard times shooting otter.
\par 
\par A. No.
\par 
\par Q. How do you hunt them? A. From boats.
\par 
\par Q. How many boats do you generally take? A. One time there were six.
\par 
\par Q. How many shots do you have to fire to get an otter?
\par 
\par A. It's a hard animal to kill.
\par 
\par Q. How many have you killed in your life?
\par 
\par A. I have killed 13 in one day, places wherethey [where they] were never hunted before. They they were worth $20 apiece.
\par 
\par Q. You made a pretty goo [good] day's work. A. There were three with me.
\par 
\par Q. Do they keep under water more than a seal? A. About the same as seals.
\par 
\par Q. Do otter ever come on shore on rocks?
\par 
\par A. No. I saw a wounded one once on a rock, that's all. An otter never gets wet alive; after they die they get wet.
\par 
\par Q. How do you know they get wet before you get to them?
\par 
\par Q. When they take them in the boat just as dry as on land right out of the water. I am 82 and would like to go on an exploring expedition. I killed my last otter when I was 70. When I first came here the Ame
ricans and English used to come from the northwest and go up there and fetch 12 or 13 canoes and come along the coast hare. That is what killed off the otter and run them off. They used to rob the people here. There were so many of them, could not fight t
h
em. Sparkes he got robbed. Took their skins and provisions and everything they could get hold of. Went over to the Island, and Sparkes said, what are we to do even if they come? l said I would fight first and, if too many, run. There were 13 canoes. We ha
d
 a great fight. There were 4 hunters there and 3 in our canoes and a Portuguese. We agreed not to run. Finally they came. We were off to sea running otter and as soon as they saw us they came as fast as they could; we<del rend="strikethrough">m</del>nt ve
r
y fast and just as we got ashore there was one boat 70 or 80 yards from us. One boat got ashore before the other was outside. This man that got ashore he shot. He lost the powder out of his gun and did not kill the Indian. Sparkes got ashore next. He shot
 and hit the Indian and he fell and got up again and ran ashore. I had always two or three guns. When I got ashore I shot. The foremost fell and then Sparkes and the other nan killed three.
\par 
\par Q. Where did the Indians get their ammunition?
\par 
\par A. Brig went - this was an English brig - went <del rend="strikethrough">xxx</del> after the Indians, and Americans too. They got the Indians downm [down] to hunt otter. The captain told them to kill us and take all the skins we had.
\par 
\par Q<del rend="strikethrough">L</del>. What year was that?
\par 
\par A. That was in 1836. This woman was found 18 years after, in 1853.
\par 
\par Q. Will you ask him if while she lived she seemed contented and happy?
\par 
\par A. Yes. She would go around to different houses and dance.
\par 
\par Q. D id [Did] she dance? A. Indian dance.
\par 
\par Q. Did she go around and visit neighbors?
\par 
\par A. Yes, all over townd [town] and the Mission.
\par 
\par Q. All alone? A. No. Always a party with her, 20 or 30.
\par 
\par Q. Were they Indians and Mexicans with her? A. Yes.
\par 
\par Q. She was a curiosity.
\par 
\par A. Yes. You see the people who passed in the vessels that passed here heard there was an Indian woman who had lived alone on an island 17 years and they would not believe it until they came to see her.
\par 
\par Q. How was it you did not find her the second time you were there?
\par 
\par A. Bad weather.
\par 
\par Q. Did they pay you anything for finding her?
\par 
\par A. No. They offered me $1000 for her, to take her around and exhibit.
\par 
\par Q. I thought you would have taken $1000 for her.
\par 
\par A. It did not look right to sell a person.
\par 
\par Q. How did she look? Was she good looking?
\par 
\par A. Very good looking and weighed about 100 or 130 lbs.
\par 
\par Q. How do you suppose the woman caught the shags? A. At night.
\par 
\par Q. How did she get her seal blubber?
\par 
\par A. They slept on the rocks and she caught them.
\par 
\par Q. What did she eat?
\par 
\par A. She would eat seal when she could get them. She had fishhooks made of bone and line made of the sinews of the seak back. She was skinning a piece of seal when we found her.
\par 
\par Q. Ask him if he remembers how her dress was made,[.] A. Out of the skins.
\par 
\par Q. What was it made like?
\par 
\par A. The skins were sown. I cannot hardly tell. Feathers all laid down.
\par 
\par Q. Had it arms to it? A. Yes, she ahd [had] cover round and looked quite well.
\par 
\par Q. She seemed to be glad to see you when you f0und [found] her?
\par 
\par A. She was glad to see us and was not afraid of us.
\par 
\par Q. Did you ever see any of the Indian skulls with two rows of teeth?
\par 
\par A. No, I never saw any. I believe I have heard of it. I never went much with Indians. They wanted to kill me.
\par 
\par Q. Did they steal your horses?
\par 
\par A. Yes. We were out after meat once and they got after us. There were six of us and about forty Indians.
\par 
\par <hi rend="underline">Charles Brown's Statement</hi>
\par 
\par Born in Prussia. My name is really <hi rend="underline">Carl Ditman</hi>. Ever since I left Germany I go by the name of Charles Brown. I went in an English vessel and shipped in a man's place as Charles Brown. I was born in 1822.
\par 
\par Q. You always followed the sea?
\par 
\par A. For 10 or 12 years. Then I came here and here I stick. I came here in 1844 with Capt. Wilson and have been here ever since.
\par 
\par Q. When did you commence otter hunting?
\par 
\par A. The year afterwards. Sent us dowm to the Island of Cerros, about 600 miles from here. I hunted there and built a boat of Monterey pine. The b
rig left us for she wen<del rend=strikethrough">d</del>t down to Mexico hunting. Old man Sparkes had charge of her. I built a boat and hunted, coming up to Memmosa (?). Made the most hunt there.
\par 
\par Q. How did you come to go over to San Nicholas? Did the Padre want you to go and get the Indian Woman?
\par 
\par A. Nidever settled at San Nicholas. He had a little vessel and he went on to San Nicholas before I went on there and he could not do anything with one boat. He said, I wish you would get a boat and go hunting wit
h me. I said I would build a boat. He said he had seen a sign on [of] this woman and he was there afterward and could never find the track again. W<del rend="strikethrough">h</del>hen I went there it was a stormy day and we could not go ashore for three d
a
ys. We let the anchor go. He thought it was in a bunch of kelp but it was under a rock. When the swells came I said we have got to get out of this. I said we have to wait till slack water, because the flue of your anchor is in the rock. We all hauled and 
w
hen the swell came on us all had to let go, so he said to leave it this way. So we stayed for three days and got anchored all right. Nothing broke. Then after we weant [went] ashore the Old Man got the spyglass to see for otter. We got on the head of the 
I
sland. The Old Man got tired. I went around the head of the Island and found tracks of the woman, so I went back and told the old gentleman the woman was alive. He said how do you know? I said I have found her track. He said it must be some of our Indians
.
 I said our Indians have got bigger tracks than <del rend="strikethrough">s</del>that. And he said, well if you think she is alive let us hunt for her and take all the man ashore. We went up to the head of the Island. There was a kind of hill in the middl
e. I put my Indians 200 yards apart{\*\atrfstart 397166855}. I did not know what kind of a woman she was. I thought she might bite or scratch, and went from one side of the Island to the other and we could not see the hill.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 
\ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid1447084 {\*\atrfend 397166855}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166855}{\*\atndate 656911770}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid1447084 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15156443 Wild Child}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256  She was sitti
ng on the side of the hill eatching [watching] us, and when we got across to the Indians I said there is nothing here and I said go back. There was a basket and some feathers. She ca<del rend="strikethrough">r</del>tched the shag and had a coat made like 
a
 coat without sleeves - had it nicely covered with sealskin. I said to the Indians you go to the hill and scatter the feathers and things in the basket and if she is alive she will find them. And we found them all gathered up again the same day and put in
 the basket. I went around another way. The Indians found it all picked up. We took a good many things to the camp before and when I came back I see the tracks again and I said now I am going to have you sure. I am going to track you.
\par 
\par <del rend="strikethrough">We went up to the head of the Island. There was a kind of hill in the middle I put my</del>
\par 
\par In San Nicholas there is moss growing over just like this carpet. I got half way up and then I see her. She had something to carry and made small stages and s
he rested. When I went up a little higher I see three huts made out of whalebone. I thought to myself she is in there. I peeped in and there was no signs there. I thought to myself where in the world can she be? I stayed on the highest part and saw the In
d
ians going where I told them. I looked and I looked and saw something like a crow sitting on a whalebone. I said to <del rend="strikethrough">M</del>myself what is that? So when I came to find out it was her I took my gun and stuck my hat on and held <del
 rend="strikethrough">o</del>it up to make signs to the Indians. I did not know if she would bite or scratch. I motioned the Indians to come along.
\par 
\par She had a brush fence about two feet high to break the wind and right in front she sat facing me,[.] The [the] sun was coming her in <del rend="strikethrough">n</del>her face [coming in her face]. She was skinning a seal before I came up to her. The dog w
hen he noticed me he began to growl. I thought if she <del rend="strikethrough">knew me</del> should run. I stepped right around her and she bowed as if she knew me before and when the Indians came up they all kneeled down. When s
he saw there were some of her color she held out some of her food like an onion. She got out some of them and offered them all some and offered me some too; but I did not eat.
\par 
\par Old man Nidever was itting [sitting] on 
the point. He would not go any further and we had a good deal of trouble for him to come. At last he came. He made a motion sign and she was kind of scared. So Old Man Nidever said to the Indians, in case she would not come could not we take her by force.
 
I said no, she is not afraid. So I took her by the shoulder and said <hi rend="underling">Varmoose</hi> and she understood at once. I took everything she had and she took a big seal head in basket and that was all. We all had something to carry. Then she 
w
ith a <del rend="strikethrough">[.]</del> ,little [little] brand of fire and she took that away and wobbled along with a strange kind of steplike, until we came to a place in the beach where there was water. We all had a drink there and we told her to go 
r
ight along. Then we came to another watering place about 50 feet down the bank and they all went down there and she went too. She sat down there and we watched to see what she would do. She washed herself all over. He hair was all rotted away and kind of 
bleac<del rend="strikethrough">\\</del>hed by the sun. We got to the vessel and she kneeled down. We had a stove on deck and she crawled to the stove. We gave her a piece of biscuit and she ate like a good fellow.
\par 
\par It came on to blow. Old Man Nidever had som
e bedticking and made her a dree [dress] and gave her a man's shirt. She had nothing but a coat on, made of birdksins, got no sleeves, sewn with the sinews of animals she found on the beach. Anyway we took her on board and we lay there for three days, and
 while we were laying there I made her a skirt out of bedticking. She was ticled [tickled] to death. There was a lot ofwild [of wild] dogs there.
\par 
\par Q. We want to know how it was she was left there and how came there.
\par 
\par A. Early times I suppose all the islands were settled with Indians. {\*\atrfstart 397166858}Northwest Indians used to come to hunt and shoot the Indians just for mischief.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15028004 
{\*\atrfend 397166858}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166858}{\*\atndate 656911775}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15028004 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15028004 Indians as savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par 
\par Q. How did she come to be left there?
\par 
\par A. I only know from what I have heard from Old Man Nidever; built a vessel called "Better than Nothing." They catched this family there on San Nicholas and took them all away except her, and when she came back to camp she found everybody gone. 
{\*\atrfstart 397167400}She had two children. She shook her breast meaning one nursing and one with 
teeth. She found they were all gone and she commenced to halloo and hunted around and saw the tracks and saw they went to the lower part of the Is<del rend="strikethrough">n</del>land. When she got there she found the vessels going away and she called "Ma
nyanna," but it never came and they took the two children, all except her}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15156443 {\*\atrfend 397167400}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397167400}
{\*\atndate -953617593}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15156443 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15156443 Signs easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 . 
They made signs for her to come back. She put her head on the ground and cried and they never came. She 
talked some words, "Kanake" - some kind of Indian - mixed it all up. The priest here had all the Indians in Santa Barbara and Santa Inez to see if they understood her. They could understand some words but not all. She got baptized and they made her a Chri
s
tian and everything. A steamer came up from below. The captain offered to take her up and show her, but Old Man Nidever would not agree to anything. She died. They gave her green corn and melon and that set her over. Shen [When] she was over at the Island
 a month she camped out with them and lived on what they did and she was perfectly well. {\*\atrfstart 397167479}
She would go off and get wood and water for herself and come back again and sit in camp and play like a child. There was a little otter (see Note) and she lodged a stick and hung it over for the sun not to shine in her eyes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 
\ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 {\*\atrfend 397167479}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397167479}{\*\atndate -953617591}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5848681 Noble Savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 . She made baskets of the grass that grows on the Island. {\*\atrfstart 397167494}
She had leaves for baskets, dozen or so never finished, worked on one and then the other, never finishing them. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 {\*\atrfend 397167494}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn 
{\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397167494}{\*\atndate -953617591}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5848681 Lazy Indian}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
That is the way she passed her time away. Her teeth. She had solid teeth but they were worn away to the gwns eating that tough stuff. When I brought her to the camp I took the skin of the otter and threw the carcass to the water and she saw it. She
 made signs it was to eat and she held it up. She liked potatoes, rice, fish. {\*\atrfstart 397166862}She did not <del rend="strikethrough">seek</del> eat much, but often, just like a child. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15028004 
{\*\atrfend 397166862}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166862}{\*\atndate 656911779}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid15028004 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15028004 Noble savage}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 She would take a bone and suck it.
\par 
\par When we left the Island it was pretty rough and we made her go below in the cabin and old man Nidever said we better turn back. She would not stay there but made a sign to pray for the wind to go dovm. She had named all the islands. I don't recollect the 
n
ames. She had names for all of them. When we came to Santa Barbara beach there was nobody living there except old man Nidever. Seeing the boys coming along on horses she thought it was awful and when she saw the cattle crawled on the sand beach on her han
ds and knees.
\par 
\par Q. Tell me about the ship that went and fetched the rest of the Indians.
\par 
\par A. Party of hunters, I believe; a little vessel. They landed at Santa Barbara.
\par 
\par Q. How did they know the Indians were there?
\par 
\par A. Went around the islands, probably found the Indians there and took them right off.
\par 
\par Q. How do you suppose they went? A. I suppose of their own free will.
\par 
\par A. Do you know what became of the Indians? A. They all died out.
\par 
\par Q. Where were they carried to? A. San Pedro. They say the men were strong Indians.
\par 
\par Q. How many were there?
\par 
\par A. I think seven. They were taken off before I came here. {\*\atrfstart 397166863}It was only the woman I catched and helped to take off. She was not wild. They all ask me if she was wild. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 
{\*\atrfend 397166863}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166863}{\*\atndate 656911781}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5848681 Wild Child}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 Her hair was kind of rotten, bleached kind of red. {\*\atrfstart 397166864}
She had been there 17 years all a lone [alone] and she made signs she had been sick, living in the dirt for days. She could not move, all alone. She was down sick, could not move, and got well.
\par 
\par Q. How did you get the story of her child?
\par 
\par A. The story they told she went back to get the child. They did not know anything about it. I understand she made signs so plain - she showed two fingers for two children and she shook her breast; 
one was sucking and the other had teeth. She sucked her fingers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 {\*\atrfend 397166864}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166864}{\*\atndate 656911782}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar
\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10376449 Signs easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par Q. How did <del rend="strikethrough">you</del>she make you understand that they took off the children?
\par 
\par A. They told come back tomorrow, "manyanna" - made plain signs - never came back. She could see us the day before when we were on the head of the island and showed fingers. She wuld not come down until we had stumbled right over her.
\par 
\par Q. Then she did not want to go off. A. S he [She] did not want to come.
\par 
\par Q. If she had felt a strong desire she would have come.
\par 
\par A. That is the Indian way.
\par 
\par Q. Did it occur to her to go to them, to want to see what happened? She might have seen you. A. Yes, before.
\par 
\par Q. Probably seen hunters before.
\par 
\par A. They all told she had been dead for years. They knew there was a woman left there. Nobody hunted for her and when Old Man Nidever saw the tracks thought she was dead until I found the tracks again, and then we hunted for her.
\par 
\par Q. What became of the dress?
\par 
\par A. Mr. Nidever gave it to the priests and they sent it to Rome. She had bone needles with eyes drilled in and she had a  kn<del rend="strikethrough">o</del>ife made with bone and another with a piece of wood, that she had when I catched her cleaning th
e sealskin. She had nails pointed for catching fish with. She had the rope nicely twisted with sinews and had it twisted as true as any ropemake could make, and she had bottles made of grass about the size of a gallon demijohn. We found some dishes of woo
d with handles.
\par 
\par Q. What became of all these things?
\par 
\par A. I gave them to Nidever. If we had taken care of the woman and shown her we could have made a hatful [hat full] of money. Captain of the steamer gave news that we had caught a wild woman.
\par 
\par Q. Was she baptized here? A. Yes, at the Mission.
\par 
\par Q. Do you know the name they gave her. A. Maria, something.
\par 
\par Q. They could not find out what her Indian nam  was?
\par 
\par A. No. Juana Maria I think she was named. The priests tried hard to find her life story, but she broke
 off into gibberish nobody could understand. Had Indians from Santa Barbara, Ventura, Santa Inez - they could not understand. Understood some words but not right through.
\par 
\par {\*\atrfstart 397167594}Q. Did she seem quite happy?
\par 
\par A. Happy as a lady. Shw [She]was dancing when anybody came. Then she <del rend="strikethrough">s</del>lift up her dress and made signs that I made her dress. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 {\*\atrfend 397167594}{\*\atnid SS
}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397167594}{\*\atndate -953617589}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 
\ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid5848681 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5848681 Signs easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid10058256 While I was making her dress she tried to sew too. I had to thread her needle. She took this hand and put it through and handed it through like a shoema
ker. She was content enough, if they had kept her from green corn, pumpkins and squash. Old Man Nidever told me he thought she would die the day before. She thought she was going to die. Nidever thought she would die that night when she came from the Isla
n
d. I took baskets that was hanging. She got up from her bed the night before she went away and took a basket from the sycamore tree and threw the feathers out. One of the new baskets she gave to me. She lived two days after we left (Nidever and myself for
 San Francisco).
\par 
\par Q. I don't see what objection there could have been to take and show her.
\par 
\par A. Made 
money for her. People gave her money here. She did not know what money was. Clothes tickled her. She was only used to birdskin coats. I suppose it was often cold weather and she put the feathers next toher [to her] skin. On the mainland, if they had worke
d it right and kept her on her food she might have been alive yet. She was about 45 or 50 when we found her, because she walked with a kind of stoop. Singular part of it, probably seen people before{\*\atrfstart 397166865}. {\*\atrfstart 397166866}
She made signs that she had seen men go  b<del rend="strikethrough">t</del>y.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 {\*\atrfend 397166866}{\*\atnid SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166866}
{\*\atndate 656911784}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10376449 Signs easily interpreted}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par 
\par Q. Did she give you any idea that she had seen the men before?
\par 
\par A. No. Ships going that way and this, but nobody came for her. 
\par 
\par Q. Had she anything rough over her head?
\par 
\par A. Nothing whatever. {\*\atrfstart 397166867}She held up her hand that way when the Indians came up and they let her know if she did run they would catch her.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 \cs15\fs16\insrsid10376449 {\*\atrfend 397166867}{\*\atnid 
SS}{\*\atnauthor Sara Schwebel}\chatn {\*\annotation{\*\atnref 397166867}{\*\atndate 656911785}\ltrpar \pard\plain \ltrpar\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 
