\s16\ql \li0\ri0\sa160\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs16 \ltrch\fcs0 
\cs15\fs16\insrsid13789363 \chatn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13789363 Signs easily interpreted (whole section)}}}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid10058256 
\par 
\par Q. Did you say she spoke some words "Kanake?"
\par 
\par A. Yes. From one of the men that had the littls schooner named "Williams." She got the name <del rend="strikethrough">N</del>Better than Nothing."
\par 
\par Q. Mr. Nidever thought the priests hired them to go and get the Indians off.
\par 
\par A. I don't think so. Maybe so. I came here in 1844. The priests had all the control.
\par 
\par Q. What was the old Presidio? A. Barracks for the soldiers.
\par 
\par Q. How was it you reenlisted in an English ship?
\par 
\par A. Left the Prussian ship.
\par 
\par <hi rend="underline">Note</h
i>: After copying the above statements I went dowm this P.M. (amrch [March] 16, 1882) and called on Mr. Carl Ditman for an explanation regarding certain obscure statements in the above. Being a German and speaking broken English accounts largely for many 
o
f the inaccuracies. Regarding the root resembling an onion, he says the Spanish or Mexican name is "Coccometas," that the little "otter" referred to was a very small one which "she hung up by a string and played with as a cat would a mouse suspened in the
 
same way."That they had Indians from different tribes to talk with her <hi rend="underline">but could not recollect which tribe could understand her best.</hi> That the Old Man <hi rend="underline>Nidever</del> started from Santa Barbara for San Francisco
 two days before she died and that Capt. Nidever made her coffin before he started.
\par 
\par J. T.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13448032 
